In this guided exercise, you will add rules to the Snort rules list and generate traffic to validate that they have been implemented properly.

  1. At the cybrary@snort prompt, type xhost + and press Enter to allow the simulated hosts to open x-terminals on the lab desktop.
  2. At the cybrary@snort prompt, type sudo mousepad /etc/snort/rules/local.rules & and press Enter to open the Snort local.rules file in Mousepad.
  3. In the Mousepad window, add the following line to the bottom of the local.rules file:

         alert icmp any any -> any any (msg: "Ping Detected"; sid:1;)
  4. Close the Mousepad window, saving your changes when prompted.
  5. In the Terminal window, press CTRL-C to restore the command prompt.
  6. At the cybrary@snort prompt, type sudo mn and press Enter to start the Mininet virtual host and network emulator.
  7. At the mininet> prompt, type xterm h1 h2 and press Enter to open two black x-terminal windows labeled "node: h1" and "node: h2" respectively.

         Note: The h2 windows will be placed over the h1 window, so it will only look like one window opened, but there are two x-terminal windows open.
  8. Minimize the Mininet terminal window. Do not close this window.
  9. Right-click on the Desktop and select Open Terminal Here to open a new terminal window.
  10. Arrange the x-terminal windows and the new Terminal window as shown below, with the x-terminal windows on top and the new Terminal window on the bottom. The h1 x-terminal window should be on the left, and h2 on the right.
  11. In the bottom Terminal window, type sudo snort -q -A console -c /etc/snort/snort.conf -i s1-eth1:s1-eth2 and press Enter to start Snort.

    The     -q option tells Snort to run in "quiet" mode (suppress startup messages).
    The     -A option tells Snort to show us alerts as they happen.
    The      -i s1-eth1:s1-eth2 option tells Snort which interface to listen for traffic on - in this case, coming from the mininet emulator

    You will see no output from Snort as it waits and listens.
  12. In the h1 x-terminal on the top left, type ping -c 4 10.0.0.2 and press Enter.
    Notice the Ping Detected alerts we see from Snort in the bottom terminal window.

         Note: You may see other IPV6-ICMP alerts, but you can ignore those.
  13. Right-click on the Desktop and select Open Terminal Here to open a new terminal window.
  14. At the cybrary@snort prompt, type sudo mousepad /etc/snort/rules/local.rules & and press Enter to open the Snort local.rules file in Mousepad.
  15. In the Mousepad window, add the following rules to the bottom of the local.rules file to detect web traffic:

         alert tcp any any -> any 80 (msg: “Web Traffic Detected”; sid:2;)
    alert tcp any 80 <> any any (msg: “Web Traffic Detected”; sid:3;)
  16. Close the Mousepad window, saving your changes when prompted.
  17. Close the most recent Terminal window.
  18. In the bottom terminal window, press CTRL-C to stop Snort.

    If Snort does not respond, in the h1 x-terminal window (upper-left), type     ping -c 1 10.0.0.2 and press Enter.
  19. In the bottom Terminal window, type sudo snort -q -A console -c /etc/snort/snort.conf -i s1-eth1:s1-eth2 and press Enter to start Snort again.
  20. In the h2 x-terminal window (top right), type sudo python3 -m http.server 80 and press Enter to start a basic HTTP server.
  21. In the h1 x-terminal window (top left), type wget http://10.0.0.2/index.html and press Enter.
    Notice in the bottom terminal window that Snort detects and alerts on the web traffic.
  22. In the h2 x-terminal window, press CTRL-C to kill the python web server.
  23. In the h1 x-terminal window, type wget http://10.0.0.2/index.html and press Enter.

    Use your findings to answer the questions on the Tasks tab, then proceed to the next lesson.
